1
00:00:00,050 --> 00:00:07,560
You're listening to: Migrating to Post-Quantum Cryptography: A Practical Developer Guide (2026).

2
00:00:07,560 --> 00:00:12,860
Harvest-now-decrypt-later means quantum-vulnerable data is already being stolen today.

3
00:00:12,860 --> 00:00:24,242
A practical, no-hype migration guide: crypto-agility, where ML-KEM and ML-DSA fit, the hybrid rollout, and a concrete inventory-first plan for engineering teams.

4
00:00:24,242 --> 00:00:25,288
Let's get started.

5
00:00:25,288 --> 00:00:33,641
The uncomfortable truth about post-quantum cryptography is that you cannot wait for a quantum computer to exist before you act.

6
00:00:33,641 --> 00:00:46,478
Adversaries are already running a strategy called harvest-now, decrypt-later: capture encrypted traffic today, store it, and decrypt it years from now when a cryptographically-relevant quantum computer arrives.

7
00:00:46,478 --> 00:00:58,137
If your data needs to stay secret for a decade — health records, financial data, state secrets, even long-lived auth tokens — then for that data, the quantum threat is a present-day threat.

8
00:00:58,137 --> 00:01:04,519
This is the practical migration guide I wish existed when I started building QuantumShield and QAuth.

9
00:01:04,519 --> 00:01:10,877
No hype, no "quantum apocalypse" — just what an engineering team should actually do in 2026.

10
00:01:10,877 --> 00:01:14,699
Now, let's talk about What quantum computers break (and what they don't).

11
00:01:14,699 --> 00:01:18,161
Two quantum algorithms matter for cryptography:

12
00:01:18,161 --> 00:01:24,038
Shor's algorithm efficiently factors large integers and solves discrete logarithms.

13
00:01:24,038 --> 00:01:36,802
This breaks RSA, Diffie-Hellman, and elliptic-curve cryptography (ECDH, ECDSA) — the asymmetric primitives that protect virtually all key exchange and digital signatures today..

14
00:01:36,802 --> 00:01:41,165
Grover's algorithm gives a quadratic speed-up on brute-force search.

15
00:01:41,165 --> 00:01:53,173
This weakens symmetric crypto, but only mildly: AES-128 effectively drops to ~64-bit security, while AES-256 remains safe.

16
00:01:53,173 --> 00:02:00,180
SHA-256/SHA-3 are similarly fine at appropriate sizes..

17
00:02:00,180 --> 00:02:07,331
So the headline is precise: symmetric crypto is mostly OK; asymmetric crypto is the problem.

18
00:02:07,331 --> 00:02:15,132
Your TLS key exchange and your signatures are what need replacing — not your AES-256 data encryption.

19
00:02:15,132 --> 00:02:17,968
Moving on to The NIST standards you'll actually use.

20
00:02:17,968 --> 00:02:22,391
In 2024 NIST finalized the first post-quantum standards.

21
00:02:22,391 --> 00:02:24,615
Three matter for most engineers:

22
00:02:24,615 --> 00:02:28,088
Standard, Name, Replaces, Use for.

23
00:02:28,088 --> 00:02:39,495
FIPS 203, ML-KEM (Kyber), ECDH / RSA key exchange, Establishing shared secrets / key encapsulation.

24
00:02:39,495 --> 00:02:48,641
FIPS 204, ML-DSA (Dilithium), ECDSA / RSA signatures, Digital signatures, token signing.

25
00:02:48,641 --> 00:02:58,149
FIPS 205, SLH-DSA (SPHINCS+), —, Conservative, hash-based signatures (firmware, roots of trust).

26
00:02:58,149 --> 00:03:05,781
ML-KEM is a Key Encapsulation Mechanism — it is how two parties agree on a shared secret in a quantum-safe way.

27
00:03:05,781 --> 00:03:08,197
ML-DSA is a signature scheme.

28
00:03:08,197 --> 00:03:18,329
If you understand "ECDH for key exchange, ECDSA for signatures," then the mapping is simply ML-KEM and ML-DSA respectively.

29
00:03:18,329 --> 00:03:23,161
I go deeper on choosing between them in ML-KEM vs ML-DSA.

30
00:03:23,161 --> 00:03:28,401
Next up: The one principle that makes migration survivable: crypto-agility.

31
00:03:28,401 --> 00:03:32,704
The single biggest mistake teams make is hard-coding algorithms.

32
00:03:32,704 --> 00:03:38,413
If RSA is hard-wired across your codebase, swapping it is a months-long, error-prone slog.

33
00:03:38,413 --> 00:03:47,199
The fix is crypto-agility: route every cryptographic operation through an abstraction that names the algorithm as data, not as code.

34
00:03:47,199 --> 00:03:57,043
Crypto-agility is what lets you roll out PQC incrementally, run hybrids, and — critically — roll back if a new scheme is found weak.

35
00:03:57,043 --> 00:04:02,235
PQC schemes are younger than RSA; agility is your insurance policy.

36
00:04:02,235 --> 00:04:06,586
Let's explore Why you deploy hybrids first, not pure PQC.

37
00:04:06,586 --> 00:04:15,865
The recommended migration path is hybrid: combine a battle-tested classical algorithm with a post-quantum one, so the result is secure if either holds.

38
00:04:15,865 --> 00:04:23,161
For key exchange, you derive the session key from both an ECDH secret and an ML-KEM secret.

39
00:04:23,161 --> 00:04:31,622
For signatures, you attach both an Ed25519 and an ML-DSA signature and require both to verify.

40
00:04:31,622 --> 00:04:33,870
The reasoning is risk symmetry:

41
00:04:33,870 --> 00:04:41,826
Classical crypto (RSA/ECC) is proven against classical attacks but doomed against quantum ones..

42
00:04:41,826 --> 00:04:48,533
PQC is quantum-resistant but younger and less battle-tested against classical cryptanalysis..

43
00:04:48,533 --> 00:04:57,920
A hybrid is broken only if both are broken — covering you against a quantum computer and against an unforeseen weakness in the newer PQC scheme..

44
00:04:57,962 --> 00:05:07,551
This is exactly the design choice behind QAuth's dual Ed25519 + ML-DSA-65 signatures.

45
00:05:07,551 --> 00:05:15,472
I unpack the trade-offs in why hybrid Ed25519 + ML-DSA is the safe path.

46
00:05:15,472 --> 00:05:20,327
Pure PQC is the destination; hybrid is how you travel there safely.

47
00:05:20,327 --> 00:05:22,731
Now let's look at A concrete migration plan.

48
00:05:22,731 --> 00:05:24,762
You do not migrate "the company."

49
00:05:24,762 --> 00:05:29,606
You migrate one cryptographic dependency at a time, highest-risk first.

50
00:05:29,606 --> 00:05:31,962
1. Inventory your cryptography.

51
00:05:31,962 --> 00:05:34,282
You cannot protect what you cannot see.

52
00:05:34,282 --> 00:05:50,892
Build a cryptographic bill of materials: every place you use asymmetric crypto — TLS endpoints, JWT/token signing, mTLS between services, code signing, stored encrypted blobs, VPNs, database TLS.

53
00:05:50,892 --> 00:05:59,570
For each, record the algorithm, key size, and — most importantly — how long the protected data must stay confidential.

54
00:05:59,570 --> 00:06:02,299
2. Prioritize by data lifetime.

55
00:06:02,299 --> 00:06:04,750
Apply the harvest-now-decrypt-later lens.

56
00:06:04,750 --> 00:06:08,981
Sort by (confidentiality_lifetime × exposure

57
00:06:08,981 --> 00:06:19,546
Urgent: long-lived secrets crossing networks that adversaries can capture — health records, financial data, anything regulated for 7–10+ years..

58
00:06:19,546 --> 00:06:27,238
Later: ephemeral data whose value evaporates in minutes (a short-lived session that's worthless once expired)..

59
00:06:27,238 --> 00:06:35,255
Data that must stay secret until 2040 needs quantum-safe key exchange today, even though no quantum computer exists yet.

60
00:06:35,255 --> 00:06:38,512
3. Add crypto-agility where it's missing.

61
00:06:38,512 --> 00:06:42,635
Before swapping algorithms, introduce the abstraction layer.

62
00:06:42,635 --> 00:06:46,890
This is often the largest engineering task and the most valuable one.

63
00:06:46,890 --> 00:06:49,787
4. Roll out hybrids, behind flags.

64
00:06:49,787 --> 00:06:58,969
Deploy hybrid key exchange and hybrid signatures behind feature flags, starting with internal service-to-service traffic where you control both ends.

65
00:06:58,969 --> 00:07:09,474
Measure the overhead (ML-KEM/ML-DSA keys and signatures are larger than ECC — expect bigger handshakes and tokens) and watch your tail latencies.

66
00:07:09,474 --> 00:07:11,818
5. Monitor, then expand.

67
00:07:11,818 --> 00:07:21,770
Verify interoperability, watch error rates and latency, then widen the rollout outward to external-facing endpoints as client support matures.

68
00:07:21,770 --> 00:07:23,705
Now, let's talk about What this costs you.

69
00:07:23,705 --> 00:07:26,433
Be honest with stakeholders about the trade-offs:

70
00:07:26,433 --> 00:07:28,873
Larger keys and signatures.

71
00:07:28,873 --> 00:07:37,779
ML-DSA-65 signatures are several kilobytes versus ~64 bytes for Ed25519.

72
00:07:37,779 --> 00:07:45,460
This inflates tokens, certificates, and handshake sizes — relevant for bandwidth-constrained or high-QPS systems..

73
00:07:45,460 --> 00:07:54,534
More CPU, though modern lattice implementations are fast — often competitive with or faster than RSA for equivalent operations..

74
00:07:54,534 --> 00:07:55,880
Maturing tooling.

75
00:07:55,880 --> 00:08:02,443
Library, HSM, and browser support is improving rapidly but is not yet universal.

76
00:08:02,443 --> 00:08:05,592
Hybrid mode is partly what bridges that gap..

77
00:08:05,592 --> 00:08:07,058
None of these are blockers.

78
00:08:07,058 --> 00:08:08,633
They are planning inputs.

79
00:08:08,633 --> 00:08:10,231
Moving on to The takeaway.

80
00:08:10,231 --> 00:08:20,027
Post-quantum migration is not a fire drill, but it is also not optional, and the "harvest now" reality means the clock for long-lived data has already started.

81
00:08:20,027 --> 00:08:27,887
The winning strategy is unglamorous: inventory your crypto, make it agile, and roll out hybrids worst-case-first.

82
00:08:27,887 --> 00:08:36,613
Teams that build crypto-agility now will swap algorithms in an afternoon; teams that hard-coded RSA will spend quarters on it.

83
00:08:36,613 --> 00:08:39,979
Start with the abstraction layer — everything else follows from it.

84
